english:
  title: Song of White Silk
  author: Baek Won-hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    White silk, fine and lustrous as new snow,
    New patterns on brocade shimmer red and green before my eyes.
    The beauty's heart is set upon her lord's fine garments—
    With delicate hands, she holds needle and measure tenderly.

    "Mother-in-law abhors me, abhors me, abhors me still—
    She will not grant me leave to practice my needle's art."
    Since ancient times, men love clever words as they love the reed pipe's tune,
    And this very morning she has sent me back to my homeland.

    I step beyond the gate and turn my back to weep in wind and snow.
    In the northwest, ten thousand miles away, only clouds and sky stretch on.
    Clouds and sky stretch on, yet I cannot see my lord.
    The distant road makes my heart grow dim and lost.

    I wish to play the crimson strings, but the world has no ears to hear.
    I can only lament as daylight flows eastward like water.
    White silk once dyed can never return to white,
    Yet perhaps the day will come when the cast-aside concubine returns home.
  footnotes:
    - The speaker is a concubine or secondary wife whose embroidery work has displeased her mother-in-law, resulting in her banishment.
    - The 'crimson strings' (朱絃) reference an ancient Chinese metaphor for one's talents and worth going unrecognized.
    - The final couplet uses the permanent staining of white silk as a metaphor for the irreversible nature of her banishment, yet holds onto hope for eventual reconciliation.
